In spite of our knowledge of the facts of his life, we seem to know little of the man. But though he is not a hero, one is bound to like him. His saulis and vices are those of his time, and they lie on the surface; as with Cicero in his letters, his frank confession of his weaknesses disarms hostility. And he has the redeeming virtues of good nature, generosity, and human sympathy. Macaulay
